<span id="freeTextContainer18107225944693111853">The book reads as a collection of snapshots and stories from some of African subsaharan countries after the formal independance. It’s quite educational and provides an overview of the historical and social context of the time. I appreciate how Kapuscinski smoothly shifts from vignettes of daily life, food, fauna and flora to elaborate naratives of Africa’s turbulent political past, while neither judging nor idealizing the societies. <br/>However, there’s something disturbing about reading on Africa f</span>
  <span id="freeText18107225944693111853" style="display:none">The book reads as a collection of snapshots and stories from some of African subsaharan countries after the formal independance. It’s quite educational and provides an overview of the historical and social context of the time. I appreciate how Kapuscinski smoothly shifts from vignettes of daily life, food, fauna and flora to elaborate naratives of Africa’s turbulent political past, while neither judging nor idealizing the societies. <br />However, there’s something disturbing about reading on Africa from a standpoint of a white european man, as it’s always bound to be questionable, problematic and inaccurate.</span>
